@subsection  Verifying Package Integrity Using @code{MD5 Checksums} or @code{GnuPG}

After you have downloaded the MySQL package that suits your needs and before
you attempt to install it, you should make sure it is intact and has not
been tampered with.

MySQL AB offers two means of integrity checking: @code{MD5 checksums} and
cryptographic signatures using @code{GnuPG}, the @code{GNU Privacy Guard}.

@subheading Verifying the @code{MD5 Checksum}

After you have downloaded the package, you should check, if the MD5 checksum
matches the one provided on the MySQL download pages. Each package has an
individual checksum, that you can verify with the following command:

@example
shell> md5sum <package>
@end example

Note, that not all operating systems support the @code{md5sum} command - on
some it is simply called @code{md5}, others do not ship it at all. On Linux,
it is part of the @code{GNU Text Utilities} package, which is available for
a wide range of platforms. You can download the source code from
@uref{http://www.gnu.org/software/textutils/} as well. If you have
@code{OpenSSL} installed, you can also use the command @code{openssl md5
<package>} instead. A DOS/Windows implementation of the @code{md5} command
is available from @uref{http://www.fourmilab.ch/md5/}.

Example:
@example
shell> md5sum mysql-standard-4.0.10-gamma-pc-linux-i686.tar.gz
155836a7ed8c93aee6728a827a6aa153
                mysql-standard-4.0.10-gamma-pc-linux-i686.tar.gz
@end example

You should check, if the resulting checksum matches the one printed on
the download page right below the respective package.

@subheading Signature Checking Using @code{GnuPG}

A more reliable method of verifying the integrity of a package is using
cryptographic signatures. MySQL AB uses the @code{GNU Privacy Guard}
(@code{GnuPG}), an @code{Open Source} alternative to the very well-known
@code{Pretty Good Privacy} (@code{PGP}) by Phil Zimmermann.
See @uref{http://www.gnupg.org/} and @uref{http://www.openpgp.org/}
for more information about @code{OpenPGP}/@code{GnuPG} and how to obtain
and install @code{GnuPG} on your system. Most Linux distributions already
ship with @code{GnuPG} installed by default.

Beginning with MySQL 4.0.10 (February 2003), MySQL AB has started signing
their downloadable packages with @code{GnuPG}. Cryptographic signatures are
a much more reliable method of verifying the integrity and authenticity of
a file.

